The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Wednesday, August 11, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																		The body of an employee of a shop in Gariahat market was found in a garbage vat adjacent to one of the market gates early on Tuesday. Most shop-owners downed their shutters subsequently, protesting the lack of security in the market.																																																								Paritosh Maiti, 40, was found dead with a few injury marks at 4.15 am, said deputy commissioner of police (south) Anuj Sharma. We have not ruled out foul play and are awaiting the post-mortem report. 																																																								aiti, who was from Sagar Island, in South 24-Parganas, had been working at Lakshmi Narayan Bhandar for the past 30 years. The body was first spotted by workers of the markets chicken stalls. They informed the police, who took the body to National Medical College and Hospital. We are examining his medical records and also investigating whether he had any criminal antecedents, said Sharma.																																																								n investigating officer said Maiti may have suffered a cardiac arrest and then fallen from the terrace, but wondered how the body could have landed so neatly in the vat.Sumita Mondal, 13, was injured when a tram in reverse gear hit her on Tuesday afternoon at Tollygunge tram depot. Eyewitnesses and Mondals relatives soon attacked Calcutta Tramways Company (CTC) officials present at the depot. An office was set on fire and a few trams and buses were damaged before a contingent from the Jadavpur police station arrived on the spot and arrested 14 persons. Guards employed by the CTC, too, fired in the air to disperse the mob.																																																		Two licence inspectors of Calcutta Municipal Corporation were suspended on Tuesday for extorting money from businessmen. Mayor Subrata Mukherjee said 29 inspectors had been suspended in the past two-and-a-half years on charges of corruption.																																																		Over 23 instalments of grants for the citys poor are waiting for disbursement. The grants, under various central schemes, are scheduled to be disbursed by Calcutta Municipal Corporation. Trinamul Congress councillor Arup Biswas has threatened a sit-in in front of the mayors room if the instalments are not cleared by the first week of September. Mayor Subrata Mukherjee has decided to meet chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee and urge him to take up the matter with the Centre. 																																																		The Eastern Railway will introduce one more Howrah-Serampore local in September to cope with late-evening rush of passengers. The train will leave Howrah after 9 pm.																																																		Tuktuki Das, 23, died after stepping on a snapped livewire on Howrah-Amta Road on Tuesday. Residents of Dasnagar, in Howrah, where Tuktuki lived, blocked the road for an hour in protest. They alleged that the wire had snapped a few weeks back and had been lying unattended since.Nicco Park will have an added attraction a light-and-sound show on Bengals contribution to the freedom movement from this week. The show will be inaugurated on August 12. Nicco Park officials said eight shows, of 30-minute duration each, will be held every day at the parks amphitheatre. Special coupons are being distributed to 100,000 schoolchildren, which will enable them to enjoy the show at 50 per cent discount.																																																		Officer-in-charge of Lalbazar Central Lock-up Keshab Maitra died of a cardiac attack on Tuesday. The 49-year-old officer collapsed and slipped from his chair, with blood trickling from his mouth. He died before his colleagues could rush him to hospital. TO Rotary Club of Calcutta Metro City for donating textbooks to poor students and for sponsoring the studies of five students for a year
